{"key":"post-16253432","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16253432</id>\n<content>Bacteria on agar is not a 'risk' but an almost certainty.&amp;nbsp; It's better for it to form on the agar where you can transfer the healthy mycelium away than in a grain jar where it's going to ruin the whole thing.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If it becomes a real problem, make your agar with nutrients such as malt extract at 1/2 strength.&amp;nbsp; This will actually slow down the bacteria while encouraging any mushroom mycelium to speed up in search of food.&amp;nbsp; When you see mycelium pulling away on its own, transfer it to a new dish and repeat until you have a pure culture.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16254036</next>\n<prev>16253321</prev>\n<first>16252367</first>\n<last>16283603</last>\n<when>1337438059</when>\n<utime>05/19/12 05:34 PM</utime>\n</post>"}